# Founder Thesis

## Why I Am Building 9930

I am building 9930 because I believe healing deserves a more integrated future.

For a long time, I saw wound care and infection-related problems as categories that medicine was supposed to have already solved well. But personal experience changed that belief. I came to understand that in many real-life situations, healing is slower, harder, and less complete than people expect. The suffering is not only physical. It affects dignity, confidence, family life, and the ability to return to normal living.

That realization became the starting point for 9930.

---

## Where This Began

This company began from something deeply personal.

My grandmother suffered from bed sores that persisted for a long time, even while receiving care in hospital settings. Watching that firsthand had a profound impact on me. It made me realize how difficult chronic wounds can be, how much suffering they cause, and how often the healing process feels incomplete even when treatment is being provided.

I could not stop thinking about the gap between care being delivered and healing actually happening.

That experience led me to look more seriously at whether there could be a different path — one that was not limited to standard categories or conventional assumptions. I became increasingly interested in how the principles and healing orientation of Traditional Chinese Medicine might be modernized and translated into a more practical, scalable, and contemporary framework.

Over time, that search became one of the foundations of 9930.

Today, my grandmother’s bed sores are gone, and that outcome remains one of the most personal reminders to me that better healing solutions matter.

---

## The Belief Behind the Company

At the center of 9930 is a simple belief:

**healing should not be approached as a narrow intervention, but as a broader system that supports recovery more completely.**

I believe too many solutions are designed around isolated symptoms, isolated product categories, or isolated moments of care. But in reality, infection, inflammation, tissue damage, and recovery are deeply connected. When healing is treated as fragmented, outcomes often remain fragmented too.

That is why I believe there is room for a company built around a more unified philosophy — one that takes healing seriously not only as a technical challenge, but as a human one.

---

## Why Traditional Wisdom Still Matters

Part of my conviction comes from believing that traditional healing systems still have value, not because they should be copied unchanged, but because they often contain ways of thinking that modern systems have overlooked.

Traditional Chinese Medicine has long approached the body with a broader view of balance, recovery, and restoration. I do not see that as something that should remain locked in the past. I see it as something that can be reinterpreted, modernized, and developed into forms that are more usable, more scalable, and more relevant to today’s world.

To me, the future of healing does not require choosing between tradition and innovation. It requires knowing how to bring them together intelligently.

That is one of the core ideas behind 9930.

---

## Why Modernization Matters

Modernization is not only about technology. It is about translation.

It means taking ideas that may once have existed only as tradition, intuition, or fragmented practice, and rebuilding them into clearer products, clearer systems, and clearer pathways to scale.

It means asking:

- How can healing be made more practical?
- How can trust be built more clearly?
- How can better recovery be supported across more settings?
- How can a philosophy of care become a real operating platform?

This is the kind of work I want 9930 to do.

I do not want to build something that merely looks modern on the surface. I want to build something that genuinely modernizes how healing is understood, delivered, and supported.

---

## A Different Standard for Health-Conscious Products

I also believe there is growing need for a more health-conscious standard in healing-related products.

People are becoming more thoughtful about what they use on their bodies, what they expose their families to, and what kinds of products they trust over time. That shift matters. It creates space for a company that takes ingredient philosophy seriously and that builds with greater care, intentionality, and respect for long-term wellbeing.

For me, this is not about trend-following. It is about alignment.

If a company is built around healing, then the way it designs products should reflect a deeper commitment to health, trust, and thoughtfulness.

That is why natural-ingredient philosophy is an important part of how I think about 9930.

---

## What I Think the Market Is Missing

I believe the market still lacks companies that combine all of the following in a truly coherent way:

- a serious focus on infection-related suffering
- a real commitment to recovery and restoration
- a health-conscious product philosophy
- a bridge between traditional healing insight and modern execution
- a long-term systems mindset rather than a single-product mindset

Many companies can do one or two of these things. Very few are built from the beginning to combine all of them into one operating logic.

That is the space where I believe 9930 belongs.

